### 2. Recursive MongoDB Aggregation (Tree Data Visibility)
We will create a powerful, reusable MongoDB pipeline using `$graphLookup` to dynamically fetch an entire cross-tier hierarchy branch.

#### [NEW] `backend/utils/hierarchy.js` `(Proposed helper)`
```javascript
const mongoose = require('mongoose');

// Fetches an array of all vendor IDs at or below the given root vendor ID
const getDescendantVendorIds = async (rootVendorId) => {
    const hierarchy = await mongoose.model('Vendor').aggregate([
        { $match: { _id: rootVendorId } },
        {
            $graphLookup: {
                from: 'vendors',           // The collection name
                startWith: '$_id',         // Start with the root vendor
                connectFromField: '_id',   // Node's _id
                connectToField: 'parentId',// Child's parentId connects to Node
                as: 'descendants'          // Output array
            }
        }
    ]);

    if (!hierarchy.length) return [rootVendorId];
    
    // Extract array of all child IDs, plus the root ID
    const descendantIds = hierarchy[0].descendants.map(d => d._id);
    return [rootVendorId, ...descendantIds];
};
```

#### [MODIFY] [dashboardController.js](file:///c:/Users/hp/Desktop/Cab-Vendor-System/backend/controllers/dashboardController.js)
- Inject the `$graphLookup` helper to retrieve `allChildIds`.
- Refactor the multiple `countDocuments` queries to use `{ vendorId: { $in: allChildIds } }`. This instantly solves the visibility defect where SuperVendors couldn't see deeply nested local-tier items.

